I don't see why she had such a dilemma accepting what was going on either - which I think was supposed to be one of the themes of the movie, the ends justify the means am I right?

text: I really liked this movie.Â  I liked it because just as Denis Villeneuve (the director) stated in an interview, I'm interested in the border wars and how that affects people's lives.Â  Poverty is a painful thing and when supply and demand of illegal drugs makes fast money, it is truly amazing what people will do for that money.Â  I think its a great insight into the troubles that America has created by keeping the Mexican economy down living in a third world state, the CIA operated cartels and the body count that neither government wants to deal with or talk about.Â  This movie reaches out and kisses the truth a little, but not so much that ignorant people would be offended if they had to deal with any kind of truth, so *whew*Â the general audiences of this film areÂ safe.Â  But for those of us who understand because we "follow the money" like this movie for it's hint of insight.Â  I guess that's all Hollywood is allowed to do these days.

text: MY RATING - 9 out of 10  Sicario could be described as grim , dark or even depressing at times. There is no joy in the story that is being told here but despite all that it is utterly brilliant.  This is the story of an FBI agent ( Emily Blunt ) who is seconded into an elite unit that deals with the drug barons on the Mexican border but not is all it seems. She is told very little and what she does know she doesn't like. This film is intense. It really does grip you. The first half an hour , especially the scenes when we are in Mexico , are stunning . The director , Denis Villeneuve , pulls no punches whatsoever and along with some great performances from Blunt , Josh Brolin and Benicio Del Toro this is a visual and sensual treat. Highly Recommended.

text: What a movie! *What a fucking movie!!!* In an age where we are numbed by constant "action" and CG destruction and cheap thrills, here we have a film with the right people at the helm, the right people to portray the play, here's where you can achieve more with less. Mood/atmosphere is really important and I don't see enough of that in today's movies anymore. This is true craftsmanship. There are flicks where by the end of it you are done with your popcorn, then there are films where by the end your popcorn was left untouched because your heart has been stuck up your throat through the whole running, films where you are not a viewer but a passenger.   IMO, it takes full score 10/10 cinematography 10/10 sound 10/10 acting 10/10 dialogue  Action and suspense is one thing, but one scene kinda stood out to me, the part where the silhouettes of the soldiers disappearing into the darkness of the foreground at the twilight of dawn.  The film didn't treat you like an idiot either(another example of less is more), e.g "you will be committing suicide" just one line unfolds so many things, it starts with understanding the ownership of the gun, then your mind goes wild with even further prognostications, when it was stressed at the max already.  Some parts are less believable though, like (off the top of my head) the strength of the gangs on the highway or the men at the villa, rubberband, or dying man *casually* drive, *turn* and stop like that. It's just Little stuff you can sweat off though.

text: Sicario (Movie): WOW, Benicio Del Toro Sanchez takes this Movie, HE carries it!  However, I have to admit that Emily Blunt was making me dislike her for her lack of knowledge--they were trying to teach her regarding the drug-world in Mexico which is happening right now & she was not understanding.   Therefore, she had me convince that she needed to go home!!  A MUST SEE for Adults unless you want your teenagers to realize the drug war in Mexico.  Also, the Police Officer, (must get his name) with the kid, he does great, especially, when Del Toro tells him to get out of the police car, the look that he gives is quick, realistic and outstanding which only certain actors can execute.   I would love to see Dadi Pinero acting with Benicio Del Toro Sanchez...Sicarii, Jewish assassins from the first century AD, however in Mexico it means "Hitman" which the Movie states it in the beginning.  The above-mentioned is no good because then people are going to expect a lot from the Movie & it should be seen without pre-comments and/or overstated opinion(s). text: The writers and directors did a good job showing viewers what it would be like for an FBI agent to join a CIA operation.  There is a difference in boundaries that each department uses.  This is why the female character has such a hard time following orders.  Del Toro's character is operating off of revenge and he's willing to do whatever it takes to accomplish his mission.  The CIA leader played by Brolin takes advantage of this and Blunts character figures that out and feels it's immoral.  Good display of good people having to make difficult choices and decisions for a greater good.  At the end however one will question if all these decisions even help the greater good.  Like the cartel leader says before his death, "are we any different from them?"
